H1> Accepting uploads safely

P> Letting visitors upload files is powerful, but it is also one of the largest attack surfaces of any CMS. e107 ships with sane defaults; the tips below tighten the screws further.

WARN> Never accept arbitrary file types from anonymous users. The [b]allowed types[/b] list is your single most important defence.

Q> I'd like to let people upload files to my site but I'm worried about security…
A> Two settings make a huge difference:

STEP> Use [b]Binary storage[/b] – uploaded files are written to the MySQL database, not to a public directory, so they cannot be hot-linked or executed.
STEP> Define an [b]allowed file types[/b] list. Anything not on the list is rejected and deleted from the server immediately.

TIP> Restrict uploads to specific user classes (see the Classes help page) so only verified members can upload at all. Combined with the two settings above, this dramatically narrows abuse.

H1> What to do once a file is uploaded

Q> I've had some files uploaded – what do I do now?
A> From the upload review screen you can:

STEP> Copy the file into the [b]Download Manager[/b] so others can grab it.
STEP> Push the upload metadata to the [b]News[/b] form to announce the file in a news item.
STEP> Reject the upload if it does not meet your guidelines – the file is then removed.

NOTE> Always review uploads before publishing them. Even with file-type filtering, content-level moderation (copyright, NSFW, malware reports) cannot be automated reliably.
